				&ldquo;I remember getting a homemade wedding invitation in the mail which had completely fallen apart. The stuck-on ribbon and lace had fallen off as had the fake flower because of the cheap glue they used&hellip;&rdquo;
			</p>

			<p style="font-size:18pt;font-weight:300;line-height:150%;">
				&ldquo;The paper was cut crooked and you could see the pencil outlines they used to cut along&mdash;it just made me cringe. I couldn't believe they could send that to people&hellip; I'd be too ashamed.&rdquo;
			</p>

			<p style="FONT-SIZE:18PT;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:150%;">
				&ldquo;I know weddings are incredibly expensive but it really set the mood for the whole wedding: I already started to imagine how awful the actual event was going to be	.&rdquo;
			</p>


			<h6>Sounds dramatic right?</h6>

			<p>But imagine that's one of <span style="font-style:italic;">your</span> guests describing how they feel when they receive your wedding invitations&hellip;</p>

			<p>You want to fill them with excitement and anticipation when they open your envelope, not dread!</p>

			<p>You want them to think, "Wow! Sarah's invitations look amazing&hellip; look, it says everyone gets a free cocktail on the day&hellip; and she's invited James along todo! Something for me to really look forward to!"</p>

			<p>Giving your guests the first impression of your special day is one of the many important purposes your invitations serve, that's why it's so important to get them right.  </p>

						<p>Your invitations should: </p>


<ul>
<li>Make your guests want to come to your wedding!</li>
<li>When done properly, reduce the amount of stress when it comes to planning your big day by providing the correct information to your guests, making life easier for them and for you</li>
<li>Set the tone of your wedding</li>
<li>Act as a keepsake for you, your friends, family and children to look back on</li>
</ul>


			<h6>

				Have you ever opened an expensive box of chocolates? </h6>

			<ul>
				<li>
					First you search for the pull-strip that surrounds the shrink-wrapped box</li>
						<li> pack so that you can tear open the cellophane in one quick motion. </li>
				<li>Then, gently pulling at cardboard lid until you feel the tabs holding it down start to give. </li>
				<li>Usually there's a layer of light corrugated card to lift up, underneath which each chocolate sits in its own unique shape on the carefully moulded tray.</li>

				<li> Some chocolates are individually wrapped in foil, each embossed with their own patterns, and of course there's the little instruction booklet too. </li>
			</ul>

			<p>Depending on the box, you might also have to undo ribbons to get inside too. </p>

			<p>All of these things add to the pleasure of eating the chocolate&mdash;it's very different than putting your fingers into a bag of minstrels. </p>

			<p>It's both a tactile and visual experience which delights your senses, and the design of the box itself is as important as the chocolates inside.</p>

			<p>Wouldn't it be great if your guests could feel the same delight when opening your invitations?</p>

			<p>It's that feeling we, of anticipation and delight, that we set about to create with our invitations&hellip;</p>


			<ul>
